# Joveo Publisher Intelligence Project Workflow
#
# 1. Purpose
# This project runs an automated weekday intelligence workflow for Joveo.
# Its job is to research recent publisher-related updates, summarize the most
# relevant developments, post a digest to Slack, and record which URLs have
# already been sent so they are not posted again in future runs.
#
# 2. Main Runtime Entry Points
# There are two supported ways to run the workflow:
#
# - Local CLI run:
#   `python brief.py`
#
# - Vercel scheduled run:
#   Vercel cron triggers the HTTP route `/api/cron`
#
# The local file `brief.py` is only a lightweight wrapper.
# The actual workflow logic lives in `publisher_intel.py`.
# The Vercel HTTP entrypoint lives in `api/cron.py`.
#
# 3. Scheduling
# The project is configured for Vercel cron in `vercel.json`.
# The current schedule is:
#
# - `30 4 * * 1-5`
#
# This means:
#
# - 04:30 UTC
# - Monday through Friday
# - which corresponds to 10:00 AM IST on weekdays
#
# 4. Request Flow on Vercel
# When Vercel cron triggers the project:
#
# - Vercel calls `/api/cron`
# - `api/cron.py` checks whether the request is authorized
# - If `CRON_SECRET` is configured, the request must include the correct
#   `Authorization: Bearer <CRON_SECRET>` header
# - If authorization succeeds, the handler calls `run_publisher_intel()`
# - The handler returns a JSON response showing whether the job posted,
#   skipped, or failed
#
# 5. Environment Variables Used by the Project
# The workflow depends on the following environment variables:
#
# - `SLACK_WEBHOOK_URL`
#   Used to post the final digest into Slack
#
# - `GEMINI_API_KEY`
#   Used by the Google GenAI SDK to generate the final text summary
#
# - `TAVILY_API_KEY`
#   Used for real-time web/news search
#
# - `GEMINI_MODEL`
#   Controls which Gemini model is used
#   Default is `gemini-2.5-flash-lite`
#
# - `GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON`
#   Contains the Google service-account credentials used to access the
#   Google Sheet that stores previously-sent URLs
#
# - `GOOGLE_SHEET_NAME`
#   Name of the spreadsheet used for sent URL tracking
#
# - `GOOGLE_WORKSHEET_NAME`
#   Name of the worksheet/tab inside that spreadsheet
#
# - `CRON_SECRET`
#   Protects the Vercel cron endpoint from unauthorized requests
#
# 6. High-Level Workflow in `run_publisher_intel()`
# The complete workflow in `publisher_intel.py` follows these steps:
#
# - Load runtime configuration from environment variables
# - Create a Tavily client
# - Determine which publisher group should be covered today
# - Fetch recent news for that group
# - Apply preliminary filtering to remove obviously stale URLs
# - Rank and limit the result set
# - Filter the results by recency and reject aggregator-style pages
# - Deduplicate articles by URL
# - Load previously-sent URLs from Google Sheets
# - Remove items that were already sent in earlier runs
# - If no valid items remain, send a fallback "no impactful updates" message
# - If valid items remain, send them to Gemini for summary generation
# - Post the generated brief to Slack
# - Only after a successful Slack post, save the URLs to Google Sheets
#
# 7. Day-Based Publisher Coverage Logic
# Publisher coverage changes based on the weekday.
# The workflow does not research the full master list every day.
# Instead, it splits the publishers into scheduled groups.
#
# Coverage pattern:
#
# - Monday:
#   P0 publishers
#
# - Tuesday:
#   P1/P2 Batch 1
#
# - Wednesday:
#   P1/P2 Batch 2
#
# - Thursday:
#   P0 publishers
#
# - Friday:
#   P1/P2 Batch 3
#
# - Saturday and Sunday:
#   skipped
#
# For the P1/P2 list:
#
# - the full list is sorted alphabetically
# - the sorted list is split into 3 batches
# - the code rotates which exact alphabetical slice is used each week
#   using the ISO week number
#
# This allows the project to cover the larger P1/P2 universe across time
# without researching the entire long list every single day.
#
# 8. News Collection Logic
# News collection is handled by `fetch_news()`.
# For each publisher in today’s selected batch:
#
# - the code builds a Tavily search query
# - the query looks for signals like:
#   funding, acquisitions, hiring, layoffs, product launches,
#   partnerships, integrations, growth, strategy, AI, updates
# - Tavily returns up to 3 results per publisher
# - all results are combined into one raw list
#
# This is intended to capture recent strategic updates relevant to Joveo.
#
# 9. Preliminary Filtering
# After the raw results are collected, `quick_filter()` removes obviously
# stale content before deeper processing.
#
# This filter looks for old year markers in URLs.
# If a URL appears to point to content from older years, it is skipped.
#
# This step reduces noise and helps later ranking/filtering work on a
# cleaner candidate set.
#
# 10. Ranking and Limiting
# The function `soft_rank_and_limit()` scores items using broad keyword
# signals such as:
#
# - launch
# - feature
# - product
# - update
# - AI
# - partnership
# - integration
# - expansion
# - growth
# - hiring
# - strategy
#
# It also gives a small preference to longer text content.
# After scoring, the code keeps only the top-ranked items.
#
# This step narrows the candidate set before recency validation.
#
# 11. Recency Validation
# The function `filter_recent_news()` keeps only items that appear to be
# within the last 7 days.
#
# It determines publish dates using multiple fallbacks:
#
# - Tavily `published_date` metadata
# - article HTML meta tags from the live page
# - date extraction from article snippet text
#
# It also skips likely aggregator pages such as:
#
# - roundup pages
# - trackers
# - company lists
# - market update pages
#
# This keeps the final digest focused on individual, timely updates rather
# than broad index pages or stale articles.
#
# 12. Deduplication
# The function `deduplicate_news()` removes duplicate entries by URL.
# This is necessary because the same article may appear multiple times across
# different search results or publisher queries.
#
# 13. Previously-Sent URL Filtering
# The function `load_sent_urls()` reads column A from the configured Google
# Sheet and turns it into a set of URLs.
#
# Once those URLs are loaded:
#
# - any newly fetched item whose URL is already in the sheet is removed
#
# This prevents the same article from being posted to Slack repeatedly
# across multiple workflow runs.
#
# 14. Behavior When No New Valid Items Exist
# If all items are filtered out because they are:
#
# - too old
# - duplicates
# - aggregator pages
# - already sent
#
# then the project still posts a fallback message to Slack saying that no
# impactful updates relevant to Joveo were found for that day’s coverage.
#
# This keeps the workflow predictable and still confirms that the run happened.
#
# 15. Brief Generation with Gemini
# If valid items remain, `generate_brief()` sends the curated news context
# to Gemini using the Google GenAI SDK.
#
# Gemini is instructed to:
#
# - select the top 5 most impactful updates
# - focus only on the provided real-time news data
# - keep the updates within the last 7 days
# - format the response as a Slack-ready digest
# - use impact emojis such as:
#   `🔥`, `⚠️`, `📈`, `🧠`
# - include a one-sentence insight and the source URL for each item
#
# The result is a human-readable Slack digest tailored to Joveo.
#
# 16. Slack Posting
# The function `post_to_slack()` sends the generated digest to the configured
# Slack incoming webhook.
#
# It also retries a few times if the request fails due to a transient issue.
#
# This improves reliability for network-related failures.
#
# 17. Sent URL Persistence
# The function `save_sent_urls()` writes newly sent URLs into the Google Sheet.
#
# Important behavior:
#
# - URLs are now saved only after Slack confirms a successful post
#
# This is important because it prevents false positives where a failed Slack
# post would otherwise mark items as already sent and block them from retrying
# in the next run.
#
# 18. Google Sheets Role in the Workflow
# Google Sheets acts as the project’s de-duplication ledger.
# It stores the URLs that have already been posted to Slack.
#
# The sheet is not used as the main source of news data.
# Instead, it is used only to remember what has already been sent.
#
# 19. Local Development Behavior
# During local development:
#
# - `.env` can supply all required secrets
# - `GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON` can be used directly
# - if `GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON` is empty, the code can fall back to
#   `credentials.json`
#
# This fallback is useful locally, but Vercel should rely on the env var.
#
# 20. Production Deployment Behavior
# In production on Vercel:
#
# - the cron route should be protected with `CRON_SECRET`
# - credentials should come from `GOOGLE_SERVICE_ACCOUNT_JSON`
# - `credentials.json` should not be relied on
# - Vercel cron should call the route on weekdays at 10:00 AM IST
#
# 21. Core Files and Their Roles
# `brief.py`
# Small local CLI wrapper that calls the main workflow
#
# `publisher_intel.py`
# Main business logic and workflow orchestration
#
# `api/cron.py`
# Vercel HTTP handler that triggers the workflow
#
# `vercel.json`
# Vercel deployment config, function settings, and cron schedule
#
# `.env`
# Local environment variables for development/testing
#
# `.env.example`
# Template showing what env vars need to be configured
#
# `requirements.txt`
# Python runtime dependencies
#
# 22. Intended Outcome of the Project
# The intended outcome is a repeatable, weekday intelligence workflow that:
#
# - researches a scheduled publisher cohort
# - surfaces relevant strategic updates
# - converts them into a concise Slack digest
# - avoids duplicate reporting
# - maintains a reliable memory of already-posted articles
#
# In short:
# the project automates publisher intelligence gathering and delivery for Joveo
# while keeping the Slack feed focused, timely, and non-repetitive.
